"font-size: 20px; color: rgb(54, 94, 153);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-arrow-circle-right"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="6" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1645998560286" class="element-wrap" data-id="1645998560286"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left"><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">Adhering to toxins and heavy metals (including mercury) before carrying them out of the body</p></div></div></div></li><li style="margin-bottom: 15px"><span class="gf-il-icon item-content" data-index="7" data-key="content" style="width: 45px"><div data-label="Icon" id="e-1645998561365" class="element-wrap" data-id="1645998561365"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><div class="gf_icon-wrap" style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(54, 94, 153);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-arrow-circle-right"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="7" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1645998561312" class="element-wrap" data-id="1645998561312"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left"><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">Regulating cellular proliferation and apoptosis</p></div></div></div></li><li style="margin-bottom: 15px"><span class="gf-il-icon item-content" data-index="8" data-key="content" style="width: 45px"><div data-label="Icon" id="e-1645998562173" class="element-wrap" data-id="1645998562173"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><div class="gf_icon-wrap" style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(54, 94, 153);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-arrow-circle-right"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="8" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1645998562102" class="element-wrap" data-id="1645998562102"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left"><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">Participating in mitochondrial function and the maintenance of mitochondrial DNA</p></div></div></div></li></ul></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1645998711851" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1645998711851"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Essentially, glutathione is crucial for shielding cells from endogenous and exogenous reactive oxygen and nitrogen species, as well as dealing directly with the causes of oxidative stress such as mercury and pollutants.</span></p><p><!--StartFragment--><span id="docs-internal-guid-07e1de71-7fff-fc95-cd10-2ed4a4fb4c0c"></span><br class="Apple-interchange-newline"><!--EndFragment--></p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1645998736905" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1645998736905" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/cf1a6be0-65d4-4471-9280-c2bc5c3ff5b0/-/format/auto/-/preview/120x120/-/quality/lighter/How%20Can%20an%20MTHFR%20Gene%20Mutation%20Affect%20Glutathione%20Levels.png" alt="How Can an MTHFR Gene Mutation Affect Glutathione Levels " class="gf_image gf_lazyload rte__no-indent" data-gemlang="en" width="1000" height="667" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="How Can an MTHFR Gene Mutation Affect Glutathione Levels" natural-width="1000" natural-height="667" data-lg-size="3000x3000"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" id="e-1640961303549" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1640961303549"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2><b>How Can an MTHFR Gene Mutation Affect Glutathione Levels?</b></h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1645998793340" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1645998793340"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">To understand how the MTHFR gene mutation affects glutathione, we first need to understand one-carbon metabolism. This is a series of biochemical reactions that delivers one-carbon units to numerous pathways.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">The folate cycle and methionine cycle are two major components of this network required for regulating amino acid homeostasis, including the three amino acids that make up glutathione: cysteine, glycine, and glutamic acid.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Homocysteine produced during the methylation process can be converted to cysteine, which is then combined with two other amino acids (glutamate and glycine) to form glutathione.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">The MTHFR enzyme is important to homocysteine metabolism as it is necessary to transfer a methyl group to the methionine.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Sufficient levels of methionine are </span><a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2073-4409/11/2/214" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">required for homocysteine to enter the transsulfuration</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> pathway and to transfer sulfur from homocysteine to cysteine.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Methionine is activated to form S-adenosylmethionine (SAM), the universal methyl donor. S-adenosyl homocysteine (SAH), a by-product of methylation reactions, is then hydrolyzed to homocysteine. Homocysteine is either used to regenerate methionine or is directed to the transsulfuration pathway. Glutathione is a product of the transsulfuration pathway.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">MTHFR also catalyzes the conversion of 5,10-methylenetetrahydrofolate into 5-methyltetrahydrofolate, the predominant circulating form of folate. However, mutations in the MTHFR gene typically result in a lack of folate required for methylation reactions.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">MTHFR mutations are commonly associated with </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/how-to-lower-homocysteine-mthfr" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">high homocysteine levels</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> and low methionine production, which in turn may lead to the accumulation of S-adenosylhomocysteine (SAH) and low levels of SAMe. Vitamin B12 and SAMe/SAH are essential in regulating methionine activity, and methionine is also a </span><a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00726-016-2369-y" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">metabolic precursor for cysteine</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">. Most tissues are dependent on the </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3775251/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">transport and cellular uptake of cysteine</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> for glutathione synthesis.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">If the methylation process does not occur efficiently due to a lack of folate, the transsulfuration pathway will also be compromised, which in turn impairs the creation of glutathione.</span></p><p><!--StartFragment--><span id="docs-internal-guid-b6c6d064-7fff-9ad7-1946-feb575d15b40"></span><br class="Apple-interchange-newline"><!--EndFragment--></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" id="e-1643348879658" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1643348879658"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3><b>What Issues Could Low Glutathione Cause?</b></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1645998861570" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1645998861570"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Low glutathione may have a significant effect on human health. Deficiency or poor glutathione levels increase the body’s susceptibility to oxidative stress, particularly in the tissues and cell types of the tissues in which it is found in the highest concentrations.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Studies suggest that low glutathione can increase the </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2756154/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">risk of developing chronic illnesses</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> such as cancer, neurodegenerative diseases, and diseases of the cardiovascular, inflammatory, immune, metabolic systems, cystic fibrosis.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">In relation to the immune system, glutathione deficiency may </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8418777/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">impair macrophage and T-cell function</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> in relation to the immune system.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">In addition, imbalances in glutathione levels may also </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2756154/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">speed up the aging process</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">. Just as low intracellular glutathione levels (as observed in many cancer cells) can </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19166318/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">decrease antioxidant capacity</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">, elevated levels of glutathione are shown to </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19166318/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">increase antioxidant capacity</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> and improve resistance to oxidative stress.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">For this reason, maintenance of adequate glutathione levels may enhance immunocompetence, protect the body from numerous chronic diseases, and improve the ability to recover from illness or physical stress.&nbsp;</span></p></div></div></div></div></div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Row" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" id="r-1627477816446" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1627477816446" data-row-gap="0px" data-extraclass="" style="display: block; flex-wrap: unset; visibility: visible;" data-layout-lg="4+8" data-layout-md="4+8" data-layout-sm="12+12" data-layout-xs="12+12"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-4 gf_col-md-4 gf_col-xs-12 gf_col-sm-12" id="c-1625746964083" data-id="1625746964083" style="display: block; flex-direction: unset; justify-content: unset; min-height: auto;"><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" id="e-1627477816382" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1627477816382" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/c3e45c59-7596-4b9e-bf1e-363867d86ed8/-/format/auto/-/preview/120x120/-/quality/lighter/Methyl-Life-Supplements.jpg" alt="Methyl Life Supplements" class="gf_image rte__no-indent gf_lazyload" data-gemlang="en" width="10" height="10" data-width="auto" data-height="auto" title="Methyl Life Supplements" natural-width="10" natural-height="10" data-lg-size="3000x3000"></div></div></div><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-8 gf_col-md-8 gf_col-xs-12 gf_col-sm-12" id="c-1625828879986" data-id="1625828879986"><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" id="r-1627477816365" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1627477816365" data-row-gap="0px" data-extraclass=""><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1625828979467" data-id="1625828979467"><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" id="e-1643239295258" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1643239295258"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3><b>How Does Glutathione Impact Methylation?</b></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1645998955822" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1645998955822"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">A lack of glutathione may have a </span><a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0304383597003005?via%3Dihub" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">significant impact on DNA methylation</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">. Although human cells are capable of resynthesizing glutathione when it is depleted, this glutathione turnover occurs at the expense of methionine. An increase of methionine catabolism via the cystathionine pathway decreases methionine recycling. This, in turn, </span><a href="https://academic.oup.com/jn/article/129/3/649/4722112" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">limits the availability of SAMe for methylation</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">One study showed that depleted glutathione could then lead to depleted methionine. This further impairs the methylation process and, as a result, </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9461031/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">significantly affects DNA methylation</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Glutathione also plays an important role in </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15606130/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">protecting vitamin B12</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> from being damaged by toxins. The interaction between glutathione and vitamin B12 may also </span><a href="https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/tx0497898" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">protect against diseases</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> related to low vitamin B12. B12 is an essential precursor in the methylation cycle and the folate cycle. Deficient glutathione may affect the ability of B12 to participate in metabolic functions, which in turn affects both the methylation cycle and the folate cycle.&nbsp;</span></p><p><!--StartFragment--><span id="docs-internal-guid-61dbc064-7fff-08f4-6e82-8cbfefbc424f"></span><br class="Apple-interchange-newline"><!--EndFragment--></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" id="e-1645998927225" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1645998927225"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2><b>How Can Supplementation Help?</b></h2></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1645999004802" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1645999004802" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><a href="https://methyl-life.com/collections/multivitamins" target=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/13631986-321c-4e0d-895d-e28c571d4b9c/-/format/auto/-/preview/120x120/-/quality/lighter/How%20Can%20Supplementation%20Help.png" alt="How Can Supplementation Help " class="gf_image gf_lazyload rte__no-indent" data-gemlang="en" width="1000" height="1000" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="How Can Supplementation Help" natural-width="1000" natural-height="1000" data-lg-size="3000x3000"></a></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1645999068016" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1645999068016"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Supplementation with oral glutathione may not be beneficial as digestive peptidases degrade it, and several studies show </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6770193/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">no change in glutathione levels</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> following supplementation. However, a study in which volunteers were supplemented with </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4536296/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">N-acetylcysteine (NAC) and oral GSH</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> suggested that a sublingual form of glutathione may be beneficial.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14988435/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Cystine, methionine, and N-acetyl-cysteine</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> are effective precursors of cysteine for glutathione synthesis. A small study showed that supplementation with cysteine and glycine </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3155927/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">fully restores glutathione synthesis</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> and may lower levels of oxidative stress.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">N-acetylcysteine (NAC) has been shown to </span><a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1471489207000896" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">treat glutathione deficiency</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> in some studies. However, this is less likely if the body cannot </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4536296/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">synthesize glutathione from nutrients</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">, an ability that decreases with age.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">The B vitamins also play a major role in glutathione synthesis and the </span><a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780123750839001446" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">metabolism of homocysteine</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">. Homocysteine may then be converted into cysteine and remethylated into methionine to be used for glutathione. The deficien